# repo-audit-triage-fix-and-issue-workflow — History

## v1.2.0 (2026-05-19)

**Changed by:** 2026-05-19 session running `/repo-analyze-strict-full` on a predictive-coding research project
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Added **Phase 1.5: Verify Findings Before Triage** between Phase 1 (Run the Audit) and Phase 2 (Triage Findings) — a finding-verification gate that runs the cheapest read-only command to confirm-or-refute each CRITICAL/MAJOR finding before triaging it.
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: acting on a phantom committed `__pycache__` finding, and trusting a phantom "no CI" finding.
- Added `swarm-audit`, `false-positive`, and `trust-but-verify` tags.
- Extended the description with a clause about verifying findings before triage, and added a `(4)` "Use when" entry for multi-agent swarm audits.
- Added a "swarm agent can be factually wrong" bullet to the When to Use list.
- Added a "Swarm-audit false-positive rate (2026-05-19 session)" subsection to Results & Parameters.
- Added a Verified On row for the predictive-coding research project swarm audit.
- Bumped Overview Date to 2026-05-19 and noted the finding-verification gate in the Outcome cell.

### Why

The skill jumped from "you have a list of graded findings" straight to triage, with no step to verify the findings are actually true before acting on them. When the audit is produced by a multi-agent swarm (`/repo-analyze-strict-full` dispatches one Sonnet agent per section), individual section agents make confident-sounding factual errors. A 15-section swarm audit produced 2 demonstrable false positives — a phantom committed `__pycache__` (refuted by `git ls-files`) and a phantom "no CI" finding (refuted by `ls` of the monorepo root, where the path-scoped CI workflow actually lived). Both would have caused wasted or misleading work — at worst a destructive `git rm -r --cached` on files git never tracked. Acting on an audit finding without verifying it is the gap v1.1.0 left open. This is the same trust-but-verify discipline that `tooling-sub-agent-pr-trust-but-verify` applies to sub-agent PR reports, now applied to sub-agent audit findings.

